                .section
                    h3 Project Goal
                    p Move more users away from legacy software products to the new system to consolidate support and development efforts going forward.

                    h3 Project Results
                    p Success!  Over a rolling 90 days, we started seeing users shifting over to the new system.
                    p <strong>Impact: </strong> Helped the business course-correct by finding features most important to users. Retained existing customers while successfully deprecating legacy products. Cut tech debt by half and reduced overall load on customer with fewer products.
                    p
                        img(src='images/aprimo/content-item-side-panel.jpg')
                    h3 What Was Fixed
                    ol
                        li Released software for larger previews with more metadata reducing friction in identifying content.
                        li Engaged implementation and client-services team to work with clients in configuring API calls.
                        li Engaged back-end team to fix forms with bad redirects kicking users back to the old system.

                    h3 What Was Learned
                    p Data-driven design was somewhat new to the org when I joined. We ran into a wall for a long period when CTAs weren't tagged in Pendo and the complex interactions required developers to write in hooks. Making a move to include hooks for all CTAs in future feature development was a great step in giving the organization the ability to monitor their success.

            .project-content-grid
                .section
                    h3 What I Did
                    h4 Translating Business Goals Into Data-driven Design
                    p Feature-driven teams I've worked on generally already have the design problem defined, who the user is, and a general sense of direction on how to solve it and where.  Innovation-driven teams though might need to discover all those things and it requires some initial research to figure out how to break down those goals into problems which can be solved by product and service solutions.
                    p In this case, the business goal was to move more users away from legacy software products to the new system to consolidate support and development efforts going forward.
                .section
                    h3 Locate Friction in the UX Journey
                    h4 UX Research Round 1 - Quantitative
                    p An initial look at activity in Pendo analytics helped us trace paths where users had moved between the old and new systems and we found that connections in the old system were a combination of back-end client scripts and users that were performing actions in both the old and new systems.
                    h4 We found:
                    ol
                        li Incorrectly configured form redirects.
                        li Incorrectly configured back-end API calls from custom client software.
                        li Most jumps from real users happened around user-generated content items.
                    h4 Quick wins
                    ol
                        li Correcting client scripts could be fixed by client services and the implementation team.
                        li Form links could be fixed by the development teams.

                .section
                    h3 Defining Problems for Product Development
                    h4 UX Research Round 2 - Quantitative
                    p We knew a few things about real world users. In terms of user journey and the AIDA model (Awareness —> Interest -> Desire -> Action), it wasn't an awareness or interest problem. The greater majority of users in the legacy system were also using the new system and had already found value in other areas. So the problem was likely in the realm of desire and action.
                    p We stalled for a while on exactly why users were bouncing on user-generated content. There were many CTAs and many missing analytics hooks that Pendo couldn't easily catch. We needed to engage development teams to add the needed hooks into existing CTAs and gather missing research.
                    p With hooks in place though, the data revealed our missing feature.  In the old system, users were using the fullscreen preview button in search results. The button was completely missing from the new system search results page. Users were using the old system because it was faster to get a larger preview on the old results page. In the new system, users had to first load up a detail page for the content item before using the preview function.
                .section
                    h3 Data-driven design and prototyping
                    p With research properly front-loaded, the design team now had a list of missing features that would help move the product towards it's business goals. For users to want to move over to the new system and take action, the new design would need to speed up the process of identifying content in search results including larger or fullscreen previews. I built interactive Firma prototypes that included larger preview options and included some metadata from the full detail page to be tested.

                    h3 Picking a solution
                    h4 UX Research Round 3: Qualitative
                    ol
                        li Usability testing
                        li Client Interviews
                    p After iterating through several prototypes in Figma and running usability testing internally, stakeholders we were able to reach out to clients still using the old system to showcase a few well-received options that included a preview side panel as an intermediate between the results and full content item detail page.


