                    p Created a plan for improving the team culture and attracting new talent including reducing the overall interview and vetting process. We launched a few digital products including a new online video training portal and a recruiting site as part of a plan to better align the team environment and activities with the core business values. Landing pages allowed us better tracking for networking at events like job fairs and school visits.

                    h3 What was Learned
                    p The overall interview process was blocking the ability to hire in a timely manner. Company values didn't necessarily align with leadership decisions. There was a need to better define personas and document journeys. I would approach this a little differently after reading Org Design for Design Orgs by diving deeper into the core values and examining where they were mis-aligned with the environment and team activities. We did reach for these areas intuitively as options but I don't think their full impact was understood at the time.
            h3 What I Did
            p How I led end-to-end design and transformed a cosmetic refresh into something that actually moved the needle using data-driven design.

            .project-content-grid
                .section
                    h4 Qualitative/Generative Research
                    p Early on I was added to some brainstorming sessions for attracting new talent via updating the website. While we did generate lots of ideas I realized these didn't have holistic view to the overall journey and were all solutions based on bad data or no data. Even validated data was decades old. We didn't have any personas defined and there was no journey map or funnel to place ideas against. So no real context about where suggestions would live and if it would be effective at driving people to the next stage. It's no wonder most of the suggestions were surface level cosmetic changes about font and color preferences.
                    h4 Personas
                    p With no existing personas I needed to do some generative research and discovery to find out more about the intended users. I wrote up surveys for existing employees to find out a little more about why they chose Aquent. Using the surveys I built an overview of common facts, problems, behaviors and goals this would give context when we looked at friction points in the journey.
                    h4 Journey and Business Ecosystem Mapping
                    p After some digging I was able to find someone more familiar with the candidate journey and we mapped out the interview process. I then divided up the various stages and grouped them into a loose AIDA model (Awareness —> Interest -> Desire -> Action) so we could visualize and empathize with the user's state of mind at each stage. Were the users just casually browsing or were they deeply engaged? Were they even seeing us? Were the common problems and goals listed in the persona research being answered to the point of having enough desire to take action?
                .section
                    h4 Define Points of Friction
                    p I cataloged points of friction in the journey and wrote user stories for new features that could be addressed by the website.
                    h4 Engage HR
                    p A website can fix a lot of things, but it isn't going to prevent culture problems like burnout and mixed messaging between values, working environment, and daily activities. I can't change the actual building or run in-person events from just a website refresh. Those items were prioritized and offloaded from the scope of the website.
                    h4 Quantitative Research
                    p Establishing landing pages for job fairs and other events with CTAs for sending in resumes would give us a great feedback loop to gauge interest from particular events over time.
                    h4 Qualitative Research
                    p I also wrote short surveys given to candidates during onboarding to give us some generative feedback on what was or wasn't attracting talent.
                .section
                    h4 Copywriting
                    p I found the book "Letting Go of the Words" particularly helpful in rewriting all the copy for the website to address the problems and goals I found earlier in the persona discovery process.
                    h4 Visual design
                    p I used Adobe Photoshop, Illustrator, and Sketch to create graphics and page layouts. Colors, fonts and grid system were matched against the parent company website.
                    h4 Imagery
                    p I defined example imagery to be used in the marketing materials, picking overhead drone photos to create the feeling of seeing the big picture through future tech which is exactly what we provide in our solutions to clients: technology-based solutions that work with large amounts of data at a digestible scale.
                    h4 Motion Graphics
                    p I drew up storyboards, animated motion graphics, and handled sound design for an internal video training library. The primary focus of this team is web development so a gear was used to show things, "working." Having the logo typed out creates familiarity with job tasks which included typing out and organizing code.
                .section
                    h4 Development
                    p I used HTML5/CSS3 and JavaScript to build out the designs and engineered a few node.js task runners to automatically generate compressed HTML/CSS from Sass and pug sources files. It also ran CSSlint and ESlint before pushing to git version control.
                    h4 Quantitative Review
                    p Internal review was very positive. I got moved to other projects but metrics control was handed over to recruiters. I have to assume things were working since they've kept the same website for 5+ years now.

